<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web States</strong> standardizes how state is managed, observed, and validated in the browser. 
        By elevating Stores, Signals, and Schemas to first-class primitives, we decouple state logic from UI frameworks.
    </p>
</section>
<section id="proposed-states" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="proposed-standards">Proposed Standards</h3>
    <div class="standards-grid">
        {% for state in states %}
        <a href="/states/{{ state.id }}/" class="standard-card">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                <h4 id="state-{{ state.id }}" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">{{ state.name }}</h4>
            </div>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">{{ state.summary }}</p>
            <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                {{ projectStatus(state.status) }}
            </div>
        </a>
        {% endfor %}
    </div>
</section>
<section>
  <h3>Design Note: Observation as a Web States Role</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Observation</strong>—the ability to subscribe to changes or react to updates—is a core feature of <em>Web States</em> (such as stores or signals). These objects are designed to be observed directly, regardless of how they are provided (e.g., via injection or direct reference). Context/injector systems simply provide access to these stateful objects; the observation mechanism is always a property of the state object itself.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="ssr" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web States</strong>.
        The server MUST serialize initial store state into the HTML so the client can hydrate stores
        without redundant data fetches.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Store state serialization</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;script type="application/json"
  data-store="app-state"&gt;
{"count":5,"user":{"name":"John"}}
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST emit initial state as a JSON script block. The <code>data-store</code> attribute identifies the store key.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Multiple stores</strong></td>
                    <td>One <code>&lt;script type="application/json" data-store="..."&gt;</code> block per store</td>
                    <td>Each store gets its own serialization block. Blocks MAY appear anywhere in the document.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>State-driven content</strong></td>
                    <td>Resolved values in HTML (e.g., <code>&lt;span&gt;5&lt;/span&gt;</code>)</td>
                    <td>Server MUST render all store-derived content using the serialized state values.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>JSON parsing:</strong> Client reads <code>&lt;script type="application/json" data-store="..."&gt;</code> blocks and parses the JSON content.</li>
        <li><strong>Store initialization:</strong> <code>CustomStore</code> / <code>SimpleStore</code> instances are initialized with the parsed state, skipping any initial data fetch.</li>
        <li><strong>Subscription activation:</strong> Store subscriptions (<code>subscribe()</code>) begin after hydration. Initial render matches server output — no DOM mutations needed.</li>
        <li><strong>Script block cleanup:</strong> Client MAY remove the JSON script blocks after hydration, or leave them as inert elements.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript, all content rendered from store state is visible as static text.
        The JSON script blocks are invisible (<code>type="application/json"</code> is not executed by browsers).
        No reactivity — content remains static at its server-rendered values.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Reactivity:</strong> <code>subscribe()</code>, <code>setItem()</code>, signal subscriptions</li>
        <li><strong>Store creation:</strong> <code>new SimpleStore()</code>, <code>new CustomStore()</code></li>
        <li><strong>Schema validation:</strong> Runtime schema enforcement on store mutations</li>
        <li><strong>Computed values:</strong> Derived state that depends on reactive updates</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for serializing store state and rendering state-driven content.
            Web States does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="protocol-change-tracking" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="change-tracking-protocol">Change Tracking Protocol</h3>
  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1rem 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <strong>Status: concept.</strong> The change-record shape, the strategy interface, and especially
      the interop layer below are <strong>provisional</strong> and will be revised as the standard
      advances. Grounded in the research topic
      <a href="/research/change-tracking-observability/">Change Tracking as Observability</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for <strong>observing state mutation</strong> as a normalized
    <strong>Change Record</strong>. Change tracking is treated here as a facet of <em>observability in
    general</em> — the problem of detecting, representing, and attributing a mutation to state over time —
    not as a form concern. The protocol defines a single <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code> contract that
    every detection mechanism satisfies, a registry that selects a strategy <strong>per scope</strong>, and
    the observable change events a conformant store/signal must emit. It <strong>never mandates one
    strategy</strong>: snapshot-diff, Proxy interception, signals, Immer-style patches, JSON Patch, and
    CRDTs are all conformant, configurable, and interoperable.
  </p>

  <h4 id="ct-canonical-record">The Change Record</h4>
  <p>
    Heterogeneous strategy outputs (flags, old/new pairs, path+op patches, merge docs, CRDT ops) normalize
    into one shape so downstream consumers — validation, traces, analytics, undo — stay strategy-agnostic.
    It is a <em>lossy lingua franca for observation</em>, not a replacement for any strategy's native form.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// RFC 6901 JSON Pointer; RFC 6902 op vocabulary (minus `test`).
interface ChangeRecord {
    path: string;          // JSON Pointer to the mutated location
    op: 'add' | 'remove' | 'replace' | 'move' | 'copy';
    oldValue?: unknown;    // REQUIRED for self-contained reversal — RFC 6902 ops are not self-inverting
    newValue?: unknown;
    source: ChangeSource;  // attribution — who/what caused the change
    timestamp: number;
    version?: string | number;  // optional causal / optimistic-concurrency token
}

// Attribution channel. Generalizes validation's value-input (user) vs baseline-change (program/server).
interface ChangeSource {
    channel: 'user' | 'program' | 'server-sync' | 'replay' | 'external';
    traceparent?: string;  // optional W3C Trace Context link to the initiating span
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <p>
    Why <code>oldValue</code> is carried: RFC 6902 <code>remove</code>/<code>replace</code> operations do
    not store the prior value, so reversal otherwise requires the original document. Carrying it makes a
    record independently invertible. <code>version</code> is left opaque (Lamport clock, vector clock, or
    document version) so distributed strategies can supply their own causal token.
  </p>

  <h4 id="ct-strategy-contract">The Strategy Contract</h4>
  <p>
    Every detection mechanism is a <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code> that turns a tracked target into a
    stream of Change Records. The native default — store/signal subscriptions firing on mutation — is the
    zero-config baseline (native-first); libraries (Immer, Yjs, a diff engine) are opt-in adapters behind
    the same contract.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
interface CustomChangeStrategy {
    readonly key: string;                       // e.g. 'native-signals', 'snapshot-diff', 'crdt'
    track(target: object, emit: (record: ChangeRecord) => void): Disposable;
    diff?(baseline: unknown, current: unknown): ChangeRecord[];   // for snapshot strategies
    applyInverse?(target: object, records: ChangeRecord[]): void; // for reversible strategies
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <p>
    Capability is expressed by which optional methods a strategy implements: a snapshot strategy supplies
    <code>diff</code>; a reversible one supplies <code>applyInverse</code>; a purely observational one
    (signals) supplies only <code>track</code>. Consumers feature-detect rather than assume.
  </p>

  <h4 id="ct-registry">Per-Scope Selection</h4>
  <p>
    Strategies register in a <code>CustomChangeStrategyRegistry</code> resolved through the injector chain,
    so the active strategy is a <strong>scope decision</strong>: a form subtree can track on
    <code>snapshot-diff</code> while a collaborative-document subtree tracks on a <code>crdt</code> — in the
    same app, simultaneously. This generalizes the validation <code>customValidation:change-detection</code>
    concern from one form to all observable state.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// A conformant store delegates strategy selection; it never hard-codes detection.
function observe(target: object, onChange: (r: ChangeRecord) => void): Disposable {
    const registry = /* resolve customChangeStrategy from injector chain */;
    const strategy = registry.active();   // nearest-scope strategy wins
    return strategy.track(target, onChange);
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="ct-interop">Interop &amp; Bridging <em>(provisional)</em></h4>
  <p>
    Because every registered strategy emits the same Change Record, one strategy's output can feed another
    — a signals reactivity graph → a JSON-Patch stream → a CRDT document — with the record as the hand-off.
    The mappings are <strong>lossy</strong> (Merge Patch cannot express arrays; CRDT convergence lives in
    causal metadata, not the record), so bridges are <strong>adapters</strong>, not identities. When
    multiple concurrent sources mutate the same state, ordering defers to the strongest participating model:
    CRDT convergence rules (least-upper-bound for state-based; commutativity under causal delivery for
    op-based) or an explicit <code>version</code> token. The exact bridging mechanism is intentionally
    under-specified at <code>concept</code> status.
  </p>

  <h4 id="ct-observable-events">Observable Change Events</h4>
  <p>A conformant store/signal emits these events; they reconcile with the
    <a href="/intents/validation/">Validation Intent</a>'s existing vocabulary so a form is just one consumer.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Event</th><th>Condition</th><th>Validation Intent equivalent</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>baseline-set</code></td><td>A new pristine reference is captured (initial load, save, server sync)</td><td><code>baseline-change</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>change-detected</code></td><td>A strategy produced a Change Record; state differs from baseline</td><td><code>value-input</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>change-committed</code></td><td>The change is durably accepted into state (post-validation, post-merge)</td><td><code>value-commit</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>change-reverted</code></td><td>An inverse patch / undo / failed-merge rolled the change back</td><td>—</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h4 id="ct-standards-alignment">Web Standards Alignment</h4>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Role in the protocol</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>RFC 6901</strong> (JSON Pointer)</td><td>The <code>path</code> addressing scheme</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>RFC 6902</strong> (JSON Patch)</td><td>The <code>op</code> vocabulary and the serializable path+op spine</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>RFC 7386</strong> (JSON Merge Patch)</td><td>A coarse projection of a record set; object-member granularity only</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>TC39 Signals</strong></td><td>The native default strategy; informs sync/glitch-free propagation and the framework-scheduled delivery stance</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>W3C Trace Context</strong></td><td><code>ChangeSource.traceparent</code> links a change to its initiating span (<a href="/projects/webtraces/">Web Traces</a>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>CRDTs</strong> (Shapiro et al.)</td><td>The convergence rules for concurrent multi-source merge normalization</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h4 id="ct-design-decisions">Design Decisions</h4>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Decision</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>One record, many strategies</strong></td><td>Normalizing to a single shape is what makes strategies swappable and bridgeable; the alternative (consumers learn each strategy's format) defeats interop.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Native-first default</strong></td><td>Store/signal subscriptions already fire on mutation — the zero-config baseline. Libraries are opt-in adapters, never required.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Per-scope, not global</strong></td><td>Real apps mix concerns (a form and a collaborative doc want different strategies). Scope-resolved selection lets them coexist; a global choice would force a lowest common denominator.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Attribution on the record</strong></td><td>"Who caused this" is the gap no existing strategy fills natively. Carrying <code>source</code> lets one mutation's origin survive into validation, traces, and analytics.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Contracts, not implementations</strong></td><td>The protocol ships interfaces and a registry pattern. <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code> / <code>CustomChangeStrategyRegistry</code> would be materialized as plugs, and concrete strategies as adapters, when the standard advances past <code>concept</code>.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section id="protocol-storage" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="storage-protocol">Storage Protocol</h3>
  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1rem 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem 0;">
    <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <strong>Status: concept.</strong> Ratified from <a href="/backlog/011-gap-4-webpersistence-project/">#011</a>
      (gap&nbsp;#4, Option&nbsp;A) — the durable-persistence facet of Web States, <strong>not</strong> a separate
      <code>webpersistence</code> project. <code>webresources</code> fetches, <code>webstates</code> holds — this
      protocol is how what it holds <em>persists</em>.
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for <strong>durable client persistence</strong> of the state an app holds. Web States
    already owns the data the app holds (stores, the change-tracking protocol); durable persistence of that
    state to disk is the same concern extended past the page session. The protocol fixes one seam — a
    <code>CustomStorageStrategy</code> registry tried <strong>per scope</strong>, with
    <strong>IndexedDB the native-first default</strong> and <strong>localStorage the graceful
    degradation</strong> — and the persistence-class / quota surface
    (<code>navigator.storage.persist()</code>/<code>estimate()</code>). It mirrors the
    <a href="#protocol-change-tracking">change-tracking protocol</a>'s <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code> shape:
    the strategy contract is <strong>the only lock</strong>, so Dexie, RxDB (pluggable <code>RxStorage</code>),
    PouchDB, or a TanStack <code>persistQueryClient</code> adapter all satisfy it and swap without touching the
    store.
  </p>

  <h4 id="storage-strategy-contract">The Strategy Contract</h4>
  <p>
    Every persistence engine is a <code>CustomStorageStrategy</code> over a named scope. The native default is
    an IndexedDB-backed key-value store (zero-config, native-first); <code>localStorage</code> is the synchronous
    degradation when IndexedDB is unavailable (private-mode quirks, disabled storage); libraries are opt-in
    adapters behind the same contract.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
interface CustomStorageStrategy {
    readonly key: string;                       // e.g. 'native-indexeddb', 'local-storage', 'rxdb'
    // Durable structured-record CRUD over one scope. Async by default — IndexedDB is async,
    // and an async contract lets a remote/SQLite/OPFS engine satisfy it too.
    get<T>(scope: string, id: string): Promise<T | undefined>;
    set<T>(scope: string, id: string, value: T): Promise<void>;
    delete(scope: string, id: string): Promise<void>;
    keys(scope: string): Promise<string[]>;
    // Optional bulk + change notification for engines that support them (feature-detected).
    bulk?(scope: string, ops: Array<{ op: 'set' | 'delete'; id: string; value?: unknown }>): Promise<void>;
    subscribe?(scope: string, onChange: (id: string) => void): Disposable;
}

// Persistence class + quota — the navigator.storage surface, normalized.
interface StoragePersistence {
    persist(): Promise<boolean>;                // navigator.storage.persist() — best-effort -> persistent
    persisted(): Promise<boolean>;
    estimate(): Promise<{ usage: number; quota: number }>;   // navigator.storage.estimate()
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <p>
    Capability is expressed by which optional methods a strategy implements — a minimal engine supplies only
    <code>get</code>/<code>set</code>/<code>delete</code>/<code>keys</code>; a richer one adds
    <code>bulk</code>/<code>subscribe</code>. Consumers feature-detect rather than assume.
  </p>

  <h4 id="storage-registry">Per-Scope Selection &amp; Degradation</h4>
  <p>
    Strategies register in a <code>CustomStorageStrategyRegistry</code> resolved through the injector chain, so
    the active engine is a <strong>scope decision</strong>: a large collaborative document subtree can persist
    on an OPFS/SQLite strategy while a small settings scope persists on <code>localStorage</code> — in the same
    app. The registry tries strategies per scope and falls back: <strong>IndexedDB → localStorage</strong> is
    the built-in degradation chain, the same most-available-default doctrine the rest of the platform uses.
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// A conformant store delegates persistence; it never hard-codes the engine.
async function persist<T>(scope: string, id: string, value: T): Promise<void> {
    const registry = /* resolve customStorageStrategy from injector chain */;
    const strategy = registry.active();   // nearest-scope strategy wins; default = native IndexedDB
    await strategy.set(scope, id, value); // throws -> registry degrades to the next strategy (localStorage)
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="storage-scope-boundary">Scope Boundary — durable store only</h4>
  <p>
    Per the <a href="/backlog/011-gap-4-webpersistence-project/">#011</a> Option-A bisection, "persistence"
    deliberately does <strong>not</strong> become one monolith. This protocol owns the durable
    structured-record store and nothing else; the neighbouring facets stay with their natural owners:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Facet</th><th>Owner</th><th>Why not here</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Durable structured store</strong> (IndexedDB + <code>persist()</code>)</td><td>✅ this protocol (<code>webstates</code>)</td><td>genuinely unowned + engine-swappable — the one earned Protocol</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Response cache</strong> (Cache Storage + SW)</td><td>🔗 <a href="/projects/webresources/">webresources</a></td><td>a caching policy over the <em>fetcher</em>, not the data the app holds</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Durable outbox / replay</strong></td><td>🔗 <a href="/projects/webreliability/">webreliability</a></td><td>a fixed mechanism over this store + the offline-queue; no swappable-vendor story</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Conflict merge</strong></td><td>🔗 <a href="#protocol-change-tracking">change-tracking</a> sync dimension</td><td>a merge over change representations that protocol already owns</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    No <code>webpersistence</code> project is minted. This protocol can graduate into one only if a real
    cross-cutting sync-orchestration consumer (cache invalidation ↔ outbox replay ↔ conflict merge under one
    owner) ever appears — until then it stays a thin facet of Web States.
  </p>
</section>
